  1. What does this data indicate?

Based on the data from table of frequency and table of statistics I believe that there does appear to be discrimination at the university. The data demonstrates that on average a men make $6731.64 while a women make $5396.91, a difference of $1334.73. If we look at percentage of faculty holding administrative roles, women make up 18.93% while men make up 81.03%. Men get paid more and make up more of the administrative roles at this institution.

  1. However, at a deeper glance points towards confounding variables which can explain these difference, hence refuting the previous claim. First, we look at the mean and median of years_uni, women â 8 and men â 15. When then considering sex and salary in this, it would indicate that men are staying roughly twice as long as women are at the university. This would also go to showcase why they are getting paid slightly more than women are. The longer you stay in a job the more likely you are to receive a promotion. Next, we need to look at rank variable. Within the variable of rank we have assistant, full_time, and associate. When considering sex and salary we have to look at the Average Salary Per Rank & Gender Distribution Over Rank. When looking for the highest paying to lowest role its on average Associate â $7584.36, Full Time â $5334.73, Assistant â $4649.10. If we look for the highest area in which male and female are working we would see that within the female population 35.45% are in Assistant roles, while within the male population 60.52% are choosing Associate roles. So these two confounding variable demonstrate that the pay difference is due to men having a higher number of years at the university alongside working in the highest paying role within the university.

Limits & Ethics

  1. Some of the potential limits of this data set are the variables deg, field, and admin. Specifically deg ââotherâ, field ââotherâ, admin ââyesâ or ânoâ. To be more specific with the variable deg and field, it should have had more fields of study and degrees of faculty. This would have allow for us to see a better picture, that is to say, to see if the salary difference based on sex was due to gender or if it was to do with the field of study/degrees the faculty had. I believe that the variables we have are sufficient in solving the question raised. However if this experiment was retaken, I would suggest to researchers to have more more fields of study, specify the degrees of faculty, and potentially add a new variable, housing cost. The reason being I know some faculty stay in faculty dorms while others commute from home so I would like to if by including this we could see if the salary being paid last longer depending on housing costs for both genders.
  2. Some of the ethical considerations researchers should make in order to collect data, maintain privacy and confidentiality would be to only collect the necessary data from your samples. Additionally, be transparent for what you will be using the data for and allow people to opt out specific metrics about themselves. Only collect data from willing participants not third party companies who donât indicate how the data was sourced.
  3. I would recommend that the university put out more salary related information based on the Buer of Labor Statistics to get a more accurate and unbaised source of information based on pay. This could allow for more people to be more informed on how much their job is worth so that they arent underpaid for their labor. Furthermore, to get more women to pursue associate positions they should provide additional training, steepen for going back for higher education, and information about the benefits of that role. Additionally potentially shadowing with people whose roles they are interested on could allow for them to have more networking opportunities and push them towards higher paying jobs. Job hopping is also a possibility to boost their income.
